# Architecture Flow Diagram & Breakdown

Below is the complete end-to-end flow diagram illustrating the fortified architecture. It maps out the exact sequence of events, including the resilience mechanisms (Reaper, GC, and Locking) and the hand-off between the orchestrator and the processing pod using the shared PVC.

## 1. Flow Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph OpenShift Cluster
        Trigger((Cron Schedule))
        
        subgraph Orchestrator
            Orch[s3-import-job Pod]
            Reaper{1. Reaper Mechanism}
            GC{2. PVC Garbage Collection}
            Lock{3. Pessimistic Lock Check}
            Fabric8[4. Fabric8 API Launcher]
        end
        
        subgraph Batch Processor
            Processor[file-processing-job Pod]
            Batch[Spring Batch Execution]
            Cleanup[5. PVC File Cleanup]
        end

        PVC[(ReadWriteMany PVC: /mnt/moss-data)]
    end

    subgraph AWS
        S3_IN[S3: input/]
        S3_PROC[S3: in-process/]
        S3_DONE[S3: success/ or failed/]
    end
    
    subgraph Database
        DB[(PostgreSQL)]
    end

    %% --- Orchestrator Flow ---
    Trigger -->|Fires| Orch
    Orch --> Reaper
    Reaper -->|Fails records >2 hrs| DB
    Reaper --> GC
    GC -->|Deletes orphaned files| PVC
    GC --> Lock
    Lock -->|Checks for PROCESSING state| DB
    
    Lock -- If Locked --> Exit([Exit Gracefully])
    Lock -- If Clear --> Fetch
    
    Fetch[List Oldest File] --> S3_IN
    Fetch -->|Downloads File| PVC
    Fetch -->|Inserts PROCESSING record| DB
    Fetch -->|Moves File| S3_PROC
    Fetch --> Fabric8
    
    %% --- Hand-off ---
    Fabric8 -.->|Submits dynamic Job YAML| Processor

    %% --- Processor Flow ---
    Processor --> Batch
    Batch -->|Reads file locally| PVC
    Batch -.->|Chunk Processing State| DB
    
    Batch -->|On Completion| UpdateDB[Update DB Status]
    UpdateDB --> DB
    UpdateDB -->|Moves File| S3_DONE
    
    UpdateDB --> Cleanup
    Cleanup -->|Deletes physical file| PVC
    Cleanup --> Terminate([Pod Terminates])


1. The Trigger: OpenShift triggers the `s3-import-job` based on your cron schedule (e.g., every 5 minutes).

2. Cluster Safety Checks (Fortifications):
   * Reaper: The orchestrator checks the database for any records stuck in `PROCESSING` for too long and forcefully fails them.
   * Garbage Collection: It scans the `/mnt/moss-data` PVC directory and deletes any files left behind by a previously crashed pod.
   * Pessimistic Lock: It checks the database to ensure no other file is currently processing. If there is, the pod dies immediately to enforce the singleton rule.

3. Acquisition: The orchestrator fetches the file from S3 (`input/`), downloads it directly to the shared PVC, logs the state in the Database, and moves the S3 object to `in-process/`.

4. The Hand-off: The orchestrator uses Fabric8 to dynamically spin up the `file-processing-job` Pod, passing the exact file path on the PVC as an environment variable.

5. Processing & Cleanup: The new Spring Batch pod reads the file directly from the local PVC, processes it, updates the final states, and physically deletes the file from the PVC to prevent storage exhaustion before terminating.



